04478nam a22006735i 9780292771918DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222019txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927719187 a10.7560/7682392doi  a(DE-B1597)618121  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF394.C78bL47 2015eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a976.4/1132231 aLessoff, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhere Texas Meets the Sea :bCorpus Christi and Its History /cAlan Lessoff. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClifton and Shirley Caldwell Texas Heritage Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. A City over Space and across Time -- t2. A Texas Seaport in Texas Lore -- t3. City on a Frontier of Peoples -- t4. Public Sculpture and Civic Identity -- t5. A Matter of Little Import -- t6. A Dynamic and Progressive City -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA favorite destination of visitors to the Texas coast, Corpus Christi is a midsize city that manages to be both cosmopolitan and provincial, networked and local. It is an indispensable provider of urban services to South Texas, as well as a port of international significance. Its industries and military bases and, increasingly, its coastal research institutes give it a range of connections throughout North America. Despite these advantages, however, Corpus Christi has never made it into the first rank of Texas cities, and a keen self-consciousness about the city’s subordinate position has driven debates over Corpus’s identity and prospects for decades. In this masterful urban history—a study that will reshape the way that Texans look at all their cities—Alan Lessoff analyzes Corpus Christi’s place within Texas, the American Southwest, the western Gulf of Mexico, and the U.S.-Mexican borderlands from the city’s founding in 1839 to the present. He portrays Corpus as a place where westward Anglo expansion overwhelmed the Hispanic settlement process from the south, leaving a legacy of conflicting historical narratives that colors the city’s character even now. Lessoff also explores how competing visions of the city’s identity and possibilities have played out in arenas ranging from artwork in public places to schemes to embellish, redevelop, or preserve the downtown waterfront and North Padre Island. With a deep understanding of the geographic, historical, economic, and political factors that have formed the city, Lessoff demonstrates that Corpus Christi exemplifies the tensions between regional and cosmopolitan influences that have shaped cities across the Southwest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCorpus Christi (Tex.) -- History. 0aSociology, Urban -- Texas -- Corpus Christi. 0aSociology, UrbanzTexaszCorpus Christi. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074529040uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76823940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292771918423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292771918/original  a978-3-11-074529-0  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK